						<summary>

						<p>On another pillar in the <hi rend="italic">kalyāṇaṇḍapa</hi> of the Viṭṭhalēśvarasvāmi temple.</p>						

						<p>1247 A.D.</p>						

						<p>This inscription is dated in Śaka 1169, Saumya, Kaṭaka Sankrānti. Irregular.</p>						

						<p>This is partly defaced and remaining portion states that the Pekkaṁḍru and others of Uppalī (village) made a gift probably, of an income <hi rend="italic">uppu rēvu sunkam</hi> collected from the Salt pans (yupaṛēvula) called for maintaining the offerings to the god Mahādēva at Bhaṭṭiprōlu. It further states that certain Amarēśvara peggaḍa son of Appana Peggaḍa engraved this record.</p>						

						</summary>
